# React Forms

## Controlled vs Uncontrolled — The Core Choice

```
Controlled input — React owns the value:
  <input value={state} onChange={e => setState(e.target.value)} />
                ▲                      │
                └──────────────────────┘
           React sets it            React reads it
  Single source of truth = React state

Uncontrolled input — DOM owns the value:
  <input ref={inputRef} defaultValue='initial' />
  Value lives in the DOM, read via inputRef.current.value on submit
  React doesn't track every keystroke
```

### When to use each

```
Controlled:
  ✓ Real-time validation (error on every keystroke)
  ✓ Dependent fields (select A changes options for select B)
  ✓ Formatting as-you-type (phone number masking)
  ✓ Disable submit button until valid
  ✗ Many fields + fast typing = many re-renders

Uncontrolled:
  ✓ Simple forms — just need values on submit
  ✓ Integrating with non-React DOM libraries
  ✓ Large forms where per-keystroke renders are expensive
  ✗ Hard to validate in real-time
```

## Basic Controlled Form

```tsx
function LoginForm() {
  const [email, setEmail] = useState('');
  const [password, setPassword] = useState('');
  const [errors, setErrors] = useState<Record<string, string>>({});

  function validate() {
    const errs: Record<string, string> = {};
    if (!email.includes('@')) errs.email = 'Invalid email';
    if (password.length < 8)  errs.password = 'Min 8 characters';
    return errs;
  }

  async function handleSubmit(e: React.FormEvent) {
    e.preventDefault();
    const errs = validate();
    if (Object.keys(errs).length > 0) { setErrors(errs); return; }
    await login({ email, password });
  }

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <input type='email' value={email} onChange={e => setEmail(e.target.value)} />
      {errors.email && <span>{errors.email}</span>}
      <input type='password' value={password} onChange={e => setPassword(e.target.value)} />
      {errors.password && <span>{errors.password}</span>}
      <button type='submit'>Login</button>
    </form>
  );
}
```

## Uncontrolled with useRef

```tsx
function SimpleSearchForm() {
  const queryRef = useRef<HTMLInputElement>(null);

  function handleSubmit(e: React.FormEvent) {
    e.preventDefault();
    const query = queryRef.current?.value ?? '';
    doSearch(query);
  }

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>
      <input ref={queryRef} defaultValue='' />
      <button type='submit'>Search</button>
    </form>
  );
  // No re-renders on every keystroke — input value lives in DOM
}
```

## React Hook Form — controlled performance

React Hook Form uses uncontrolled inputs internally but provides a controlled-like API. It re-renders components only when necessary.

```tsx
import { useForm, SubmitHandler } from 'react-hook-form';

type Inputs = { email: string; password: string };

function LoginForm() {
  const {
    register,      // connect input to RHF
    handleSubmit,  // wraps onSubmit, prevents default, validates
    watch,         // subscribe to field values
    formState: { errors, isSubmitting },
  } = useForm<Inputs>();

  const onSubmit: SubmitHandler<Inputs> = async (data) => {
    await login(data);
  };

  return (
    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit(onSubmit)}>
      <input type='email' {...register('email', {
        required: 'Email required',
        pattern: { value: /\S+@\S+/, message: 'Invalid email' },
      })} />
      {errors.email && <span>{errors.email.message}</span>}
      <button disabled={isSubmitting}>Login</button>
    </form>
  );
}
```

```
RHF under the hood:
  register() attaches ref + event listeners to input
  Tracks values in internal ref (not state) → NO re-renders on type
  Re-renders only on: submit, error state change, watch()
  10x fewer renders than pure controlled form for large forms
```

## Form Validation Strategies

```
Strategy 1: Validate on submit only
  Simple. No live error feedback.
  Use for: short forms, good defaults.

Strategy 2: Validate on blur (field touched)
  Errors appear after user leaves field.
  Less noisy than validate-on-change.

Strategy 3: Validate on change
  Real-time feedback. Most renders.
  Use for: password strength, search autocomplete.

Zod schema validation (library):
  const schema = z.object({
    email: z.string().email(),
    age:   z.number().min(18),
  });
  const result = schema.safeParse(formData);
  if (!result.success) { /* result.error.flatten() */ }

RHF + Zod resolver:
  useForm({ resolver: zodResolver(schema) })
  → automatic type inference + validation in one step
```

## Difficult Input Types

```tsx
// Checkbox
const [agreed, setAgreed] = useState(false);
<input type='checkbox' checked={agreed} onChange={e => setAgreed(e.target.checked)} />
//                      ^^^^^ not value!  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ .checked not .value

// Select
const [role, setRole] = useState('user');
<select value={role} onChange={e => setRole(e.target.value)}>
  <option value='user'>User</option>
  <option value='admin'>Admin</option>
</select>

// File input — always uncontrolled
<input type='file' ref={fileRef} />
// fileRef.current.files[0] on submit
// Cannot set value on file input (browser security)
```

## Dynamic Fields (Field Arrays)

```tsx
// Problem: adding/removing fields in a form
const [items, setItems] = useState([{ name: '', qty: 1 }]);

function addItem() {
  setItems(prev => [...prev, { name: '', qty: 1 }]);
}

return items.map((item, i) => (
  <div key={i}>  {/* ← ideally use stable id */}
    <input value={item.name} onChange={e => {
      setItems(prev => prev.map((it, j) =>
        j === i ? { ...it, name: e.target.value } : it
      ));
    }} />
  </div>
));
// RHF's useFieldArray is much cleaner for this pattern
```

## Common Pitfalls
- Using `value` without `onChange` — React renders input as read-only (controlled, no setter)
- Mixing `value` and `defaultValue` on the same input — undefined to defined transition (uncontrolled → controlled warning)
- `e.target.value` vs `e.target.checked` for checkboxes
- File inputs cannot be controlled — always use ref
- Using array index as key for dynamic fields — reorder breaks input state

## Connections
- **react-state-effects** — useState drives controlled inputs; useReducer for complex form state
- **ts-utility-types** — Partial/Required for form field types
- **react-hooks** — useRef for uncontrolled inputs, custom hooks for form logic extraction
